thoughts.a: Input and output grids are the same sizes. The input grid contains some number of horizontal and vertical grain lines that span the entire input grid, establishing a supergrid, with generally a black color background that fills in the subsections. Additionally, there are a bunch of green tiles that are seemingly scattered at random across the entirety of the input grid, including on the gray lines. The output grid contains these gray colored lines in their exact location as in the input grid. However, the difference in the output grid is that all of the green tiles that were scattered within the subsections of the input grid are now gone, and additionally every intersection of the gray lines have instead become green tiles. Thus, the hypothesis is the following. Input grid will contain some number of horizontal and vertical lines, making a supergrid, dividing the input grid into some number of subsections. Subsections will generally be some background color and then there will be an additional randomly scattered colored tiles throughout the subsection and sometimes on these lines. To construct the output grid, we essentially copy the input grid over, but with the following changes. We get rid of all of the randomly scattered other colored tiles that are in the subsections and on the lines, while also labeling all the intersections of the gray lines with that color tile, in this pair it was green but it could be some other color as well.
thoughts.b: Input grid contains horizontal and vertical gray lines, making six intersections in its supergrid. There's some number of subsections and a bunch of red scattered tiles that exist in the subsections and on the gray lines themselves. According to the hypothesis, we need to copy over the input grid to the output grid exactly as is, but with the following changes. All of the randomly scattered red tiles are cleaned up within the subsections and on the gray line and therefore turned into the black background color. Additionally, the intersections of the gray lines are labeled as red instead of grey. Because this is what is present in the output grid, the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.c: The input grid again contains horizontal and vertical gray lines making a super grid. There are many subsections in this pair. The background color is still black and we have a bunch of scattered yellow tiles throughout the input grid. Then we need to identify every intersection the of gray lines and label those as yellow instead of gray. Because this is what is shown in the output grid for this pair, the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.d: We apply the hypothesis here. The input grid contains a number of periodic horizontal and vertical gray lines, creating a super grid and different subsections. Those sections have a black colored background along with a bunch of blue tiles that are scattered throughout the input grid, sometimes landing in the subsections and sometimes on the gray lines themselves. According to the hypothesis, in order to construct the output grid, we need to clean up all of these random blue tiles by changing their locations' color to black background color if they exist in the subsection, and to gray if they appeared on any gray line. Then, for every intersection of gray lines that we identify in the input grid, in the output grid these intersection tiles need to be changed to blue, because that's the color of the random scattered tiles.
